      "bug_description": "The solution assumes that if every node has even degree in the multiset of query endpoints, then any choice of simple paths (specifically the BFS‑shortest paths) will make all edge weights even. This is false: the parity of edge usage depends on the specific paths chosen. The code outputs arbitrary BFS paths, which can leave many edges with odd weight even when a feasible assignment exists. For example, in a triangle graph with queries (1,2), (2,3), (3,1) the code prints three direct edges, each used once, resulting in odd edge weights, while a different choice of paths would satisfy the requirement.",
      "verdict": "CONFIRMED",
      "reasoning": "The algorithm only checks node endpoint parity and then greedily assigns shortest paths without guaranteeing edge parity. Counterexample (triangle graph) shows node degrees are even, but the produced paths give odd edge weights, violating the problem constraints. Hence the solution is incorrect."
    }
  ]
}

